A year ago today, I lost one of the most incredible people that I have ever met, and one of my closest friends to COVID-19. For days now, I have been struggling to find the words to say and the right picture to share alongside them. But I’ve realized that’s impossible. There are not enough words, and if I could share all the pictures I would, because it’s not possible to narrow it down to just one. 

Carl, we had so many incredible adventures together, and I have hundreds of pictures and memories that I will cherish for the rest of my life. 

It’s been a year now, and I still cannot believe that you are gone. I haven’t posted anything about this until now because it hurts too much. I miss you so much… I’m still struggling to accept the fact that you are no longer with us. I am in tears trying to make this post, because putting it into writing makes it feel that much more real, and the wound feel that much more raw. 

I am so thankful for every moment that I got to spend with you. You had a heart of gold, and would go above and beyond to help those around you. You impacted the lives of so many people, myself included. Because I knew you, I have been changed for good. 

Until we meet again. I love you, Carl. 

•10/31/1966 - 02/12/2022•

There is a swelling storm
And I’m caught up in the middle of it all
And it takes control
Of the person that I thought I was
The one I used to know
But there is a light
In the dark, and I feel its warmth
In my hands and my heart
Why can’t I hold on?
It comes and goes in waves
It always does, always does
We watch as our young hearts fade
Into the flood, into the flood
The freedom of falling
A feeling I thought was set in stone
It slips through my fingers
I’m trying hard to let go
It comes and goes in waves
It comes and goes in waves
And carries us away
Through the wind
Down to the place we used to lay when we were kids
Memories of a stolen place
Caught in the silence
An echo lost in space

It’s taken me a while to find the words to write this. I’m heartbroken. I cannot believe that for over 16 years I’ve been blessed to call you my friend. From all of the endless hilarious memories on the Great Lawn after school to the countless hours spent together in Section 203 with the beloved Bleacher Creatures cheering on our Yankees! I am grateful for every moment I got to spend with you. Your presence and just everything about you brought such joy and fun and light to everyone around you. You fought long and hard, and although you are no longer with us, you have left a lasting impact on each and every person around you. I can only hope that you are now finally at peace and no longer suffering. Although Section 203 will never be the same without you, I know we will all still be thinking of you as we watch and cheer on the team that we all love so much. Your family, friends, loved ones and all of those around you are in my prayers. 

Thank you for all of the memories. Thank you for blessing us all with your beautiful smile, sense of humor and strength. You will never be forgotten. 💙🤍💙🤍💙
